<br>
The reason I ask these questions is because, I have yet to find any indication that there is something &quot;eternal&quot; about my eixstence.  I don't have any recollection of events that happened &quot;before&quot; my birth.  The world &quot;eternal&quot; is defined as &quot;Being without beginning or end; existing outside of time&quot;.  (<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.dictionary.com/search?q=eternal)">www.dictionary.com/search?q=eternal)</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END-->  If my &quot;soul&quot; was created within this space-time continuum at the time of conception, surely it is confined within this space-time continuum and is not eternal?<br>
<br>
I think it is either wishful thinking, fear of death, or outright arrogance to think that we are in some way immortal.  As far as I can tell, I did not exist in any meaningful way (as a sentient being) before conception, why should I believe that I should continue to exist as a sentient being after my body decomposes?<br>
<br>
Honestly, if I won't &quot;live&quot; forever in some meaningful fashion, I really could care less even if God DID exist.  His existence would be irrelevant (to my situation).  I'm curious what makes people think they will exist forever ... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uganndon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ganndon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 91<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/6/02 3:03:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=858.topic&index=534>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Everlasting existence?</span><hr size=1> <br>
